english:
  title: A Memorial of Sincere Remonstrance
  author: Lee Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant speaks. On the thirteenth day of the seventh month, the emissary Kang In-yu and others returned bearing the imperial edict, which commanded: "Since your kingdom harbors intentions to spy upon the celestial court, you must send two to three hundred officials and scholars, along with five to six hundred eunuchs to these lands." Overwhelmed by such gravity and reverence, your servant cannot restrain himself from laying bare his heart.

    The wisdom of the sage spreads boundlessly—its depths cannot be measured. The heavenly majesty towers near, trembling with awesome force. Thus does your servant offer these humble sentiments, presuming to trouble the imperial ears.

    Your servant reflects: though ignorant and unschooled, bereft of learning and wisdom, fortune has preserved within us the natural principles of human conduct and cosmic order. We recognize the will of heaven and the true heart of man. Devoted to benevolence and righteousness, having already pledged our allegiance as vassals, how could we harbor deceit and treachery to deceive our sovereign?

    Consider that our small kingdom dwells remote, hemmed in by barren frontiers. From ancient times, the customs here have been confined by geography. Our language barely expresses our own intentions; our speech requires interpreters to be understood. Though we have long wished to send but six or seven promising youths to master the classics and study law, how could we ever gather two or three hundred scholars? And how could we dare comply with such commands, which would surely serve as instruments of espionage?

    Regarding both the eunuchs summoned and the scholars already permitted—we face an impossible choice: we must avoid suspicion, yet we must obey imperial decree. Caught between advance and retreat, we know not what to do.

    Your servant humbly begs: let the thunder of heaven's wrath be withdrawn. Let the boundless mercy of heaven and earth be revealed. Take pity upon your servant, who strives to practice propriety yet knows not what propriety truly is; who seeks to serve with loyalty yet knows not what loyalty truly means. Do not demand the impossible, but grant us according to our humble capacity. Your servant vows to fulfill his duties as a vassal with ever greater care, and to contemplate eternally how civilization spreads to distant lands, forever praying for your majesty's longevity through ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This memorial was submitted by Lee Suk (1328-1396), a prominent Korean scholar and statesman of the Goryeo-Joseon transition period, likely in response to Ming imperial demands.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'small kingdom' referenced is Korea, which maintained tributary relations with the Ming court.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'civilization spreading to distant lands' (聲敎之漸東漸) employs classical language suggesting the gradual diffusion of Confucian learning and imperial culture to the eastern regions.
